Countries with cases but no ongoing transmission
---
Germany ex Maldives. 27 Sep 2016. (conf.) The patient is a 34-year-old male tourist, who visited the Maldives from 3-13 Jun 2016 (relevant for cross-reacting antibodies with regard to Zika virus assays). On 16 Jun 2016 he developed retro-orbital pain and on 17 Jun 2016 a diffuse maculopapular rash that spared his face and hands, and joint pains in the wrists, ankles, proximal interphalangeal joints. He presented initially on 22 Jun 2016 (day 6 after symptom onset) at the outpatient department of the Division of Infectious Diseases and Tropical Medicine at LMU. Upon presentation the only remaining symptom was arthralgia. No symptoms were present after 8 days.

The diagnosis of a ZIKV infection was established by ZIKV IgG and IgM through an IFAT assay. ZIKV was also confirmed directly using a commercially available real-time reverse transcriptase assay RealStar Zika RT PCR Kit (Altona, Hamburg, Germany) in whole blood and urine samples on day 6. Urine samples did not turn positive again, whereas whole blood remained positive until 26 Jul 2016 (day 40 after symptom onset). The symptoms subsided altogether after about 8 days. Ejaculate, oral swabs and serum did not show any positive result at any time. The viral strain was identified by an in-house PCR assay as the Asian lineage that is also responsible for the ZIKV outbreak in Latin America.

The Maldives are listed in the recent WHO Zika Situational Report of 22 Sep 2016 as a country with known prior ZIKV transmission (country category 3: transmission in 2015 and before) but with no reported transmission in 2016. However, this case is evidence of ongoing ZIKV transmission. The Maldives are widely considered as "safe" for honeymoon couples and those wishing to become pregnant (babymoon), for whom currently many destinations in the tropical regions of the world are off limits due to ongoing Zika transmission. However, the Maldives should now also be considered as a destination of ongoing transmission.

Report submitted by Guenter Froeschl, Kristina Huber, Frank von Sonnenburg, and Silke Woelfel Munich GeoSentinel Site and Patricia Schlagenhauf, Chair - GeoSentinel Tracking & Communications Working Group via Davidson H. Hamer, MD, GeoSentinel Principal Investigator, Professor of Global Health and Medicine, Boston University Schools of Public Health and Medicine. [ProMED thanks these individuals for submitting this report. - Mod.TY]

