[6] Diagnostic test
Date: Mon 26 Sep 2016
Source: Reuters [edited]
http://www.reuters.com/article/us-vela-diagnostics-fda-idUSKCN11W1BO


Vela Diagnostics said its test for the Zika virus had received "emergency use authorization" from the U.S. Food and Drug Administration [FDA].

The test, already approved in Europe, is validated for plasma, serum and urine samples, the Singapore-based company said on Monday [26 Sep 2016].

The FDA issues such emergency use authorization during public health emergencies, to quickly deploy unapproved medical products for as long as they are needed. The regulator last month [August 2016] issued a similar authorization for a Zika diagnostics test from Swiss drugmaker Roche.

Zika, which was detected in Brazil, has spread to the Americas and is associated with microcephaly, a birth defect characterized by an unusually small head and potential developmental problems. In adults, it has been linked to Guillain-Barré syndrome, a temporary paralysis.

The disease has since spread to parts of Southeast Asia. [The virus was already present in Southeast Asia. - Mod.TY]

[Reporting by Akankshita Mukhopadhyay and Natalie Grover in Bengaluru; editing by Sriraj Kalluvila]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[There is an internal controversy within the CDC about which diagnostic test is best (https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/to-your-health/wp/2016/09/27/cdc-whistleblower-claims-agency-has-been-using-wrong-zika-test/). Because Zika, dengue and chikungunya virus infections are clinically similar in many cases, having a rapid and sensitive diagnostic test that can differentiate them is important, especially for pregnant women at risk of teratogenic effects of their fetuses. - Mod.TY]

